- Hi.
- Hi.

23
00:02:17,246 --> 00:02:19,367
I got a cup for you, too.

24
00:02:19,367 --> 00:02:22,321
I don't think it's too cold,
but you could stick a finger in and see.

25
00:02:22,321 --> 00:02:23,758
Had some at home.

26
00:02:23,758 --> 00:02:25,631
I'm so relieved to see you.

27
00:02:25,631 --> 00:02:28,974
I mean, I read about what happened 
to you last year with that maniac.

28
00:02:28,974 --> 00:02:31,334
But you're doing well?

29
00:02:33,295 --> 00:02:36,541
I thought maybe you would call.

30
00:02:36,541 --> 00:02:39,208
I wanted to give you your space.

31
00:02:39,208 --> 00:02:41,489
You look fine.

32
00:02:42,279 --> 00:02:45,405
- So do you.
- It's 'cause I'm happy.

33
00:02:45,405 --> 00:02:48,550
It's 'cause I'm getting married.

34
00:02:48,550 --> 00:02:50,744
That's why you wanted to see me?

35
00:02:50,744 --> 00:02:52,973
Lilly, when you know
someone's right for you,

36
00:02:52,973 --> 00:02:55,038
you just feel it undeniably in your bones.

37
00:02:55,038 --> 00:02:57,142
You ever had that feeling?

38
00:02:58,528 --> 00:03:01,104
- What's his name?
- Jackie.

39
00:03:01,104 --> 00:03:03,897
So will you let me buy you
a beautiful dress and shoes

40
00:03:03,897 --> 00:03:06,569
and will you be my maid of honor?

41
00:03:06,569 --> 00:03:10,073
- What about Chris?
- You're my firstborn. Chris will understand.

42
00:03:10,073 --> 00:03:12,883
- You can't find her, can you?
- Your sister's not like you and me.

43
00:03:12,883 --> 00:03:15,914
- She doesn't need a home base.
- She's running from the law, mom.

44
00:03:15,914 --> 00:03:18,720
Lilly, watch what you say about 
your sister. / Yeah, I'm really busy. So...

45
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:21,516
Yeah, I know, your job's important 
to you. / Well, yeah, we're overloaded.

46
00:03:21,516 --> 00:03:24,307
Sorry. / Right.
Well, don't have to make a decision now.

47
00:03:24,307 --> 00:03:26,159
Have dinner with me and Jackie.

48
00:03:26,159 --> 00:03:29,433
I'll see. Okay.

49
00:03:35,849 --> 00:03:39,247
My great-grandmother was murdered in 1929.

50
00:03:39,830 --> 00:03:42,007
1929.

51
00:03:42,565 --> 00:03:43,398
All right.

52
00:03:43,398 --> 00:03:44,962
I know it was a long time ago,

53
00:03:44,962 --> 00:03:48,694
but I felt like I had to
come in here for myself.

54
00:03:48,694 --> 00:03:50,780
I've been preparing,
doing the family history,

55
00:03:50,780 --> 00:03:54,324
and I found this online.

56
00:03:55,604 --> 00:03:58,852
- A death certificate.
- All I've got.

57
00:03:58,852 --> 00:04:02,359
There's no relatives listed,
just the boarding house where she lived.

58
00:04:02,359 --> 00:04:06,259
She gave up my grandmother for adoption,
so all we've ever known is her name.

59
00:04:06,259 --> 00:04:08,633
Violet Polley.

60
00:04:08,633 --> 00:04:11,855
That's not a lot for us to go on.

61
00:04:12,186 --> 00:04:15,565
Detective Rush?
Aimee Goodman. / Hi.

62
00:04:15,565 --> 00:04:19,352
Aimee's great-grandmother
was murdered in '29.

63
00:04:19,352 --> 00:04:20,978
'29, huh?

64
00:04:20,978 --> 00:04:22,796
Do you ever feel like
you want to change your life,

65
00:04:22,796 --> 00:04:25,773
but you can't outrun
your screwed-up family?

66
00:04:25,773 --> 00:04:27,419
Yeah.

67
00:04:28,296 --> 00:04:32,833
Well, the women in my family
have not had the greatest lives.

68
00:04:32,833 --> 00:04:37,832
I think it goes back to Violet.
Like a curse hanging over us.

69
