00:05:25,564 --> 00:05:30,587
Violet Polley, found dead
on Christmas day, 1929.

88
00:05:30,587 --> 00:05:34,270
Cause of death, fractured skull
from a blow to the head.

89
00:05:34,270 --> 00:05:36,474
Photo doesn't show a lot of blood
at the crime scene.

90
00:05:36,474 --> 00:05:38,992
So she didn't die there.
Body was dumped.

91
00:05:38,992 --> 00:05:42,545
Looks like she didn't have family
to spend the holidays with. None listed.

92
00:05:42,545 --> 00:05:45,072
Home address is Darlington
boarding house in old city.

93
00:05:45,072 --> 00:05:47,699
- I know that place.
- It's on the historical register.

94
00:05:47,699 --> 00:05:49,668
Susan B. Anthony lived there for a time.

95
00:05:49,668 --> 00:05:52,002
Made us go there in junior high.

96
00:05:52,002 --> 00:05:53,920
Can't remember a thing
except the gift shop.

97
00:05:53,920 --> 00:05:56,971
Guys in evidence whined at me like
a bunch of pre-teens.

98
00:05:56,971 --> 00:05:59,286
Guess they hate dust.

99
00:05:59,286 --> 00:06:05,059
All the belongings Violet had with her
when the body was found.

100
00:06:06,025 --> 00:06:07,899
What's that?

101
00:06:07,899 --> 00:06:11,067
A rattle. / For her baby.
Aimee's grandmother.

102
00:06:11,067 --> 00:06:13,135
- We know who the father was?
- No one knows.

103
00:06:13,135 --> 00:06:15,612
Don't even know specifically 
when the baby was born.

104
00:06:15,612 --> 00:06:19,111
Just that she was brought up at
st. Mary's orphanage in Germantown.

105
00:06:19,111 --> 00:06:20,626
Start with the Darlington boarding house,

106
00:06:20,626 --> 00:06:24,726
maybe they can fill in the
gaps on Violet staying there. / Okay.

107
00:06:26,290 --> 00:06:28,353
How'd it go with your mom this morning?

108
00:06:28,353 --> 00:06:30,701
She's getting married.

109
00:06:32,258 --> 00:06:34,789
For the fourth time.

110
00:06:37,741 --> 00:06:40,590
That quilt was made from hand.

111
00:06:40,590 --> 00:06:42,591
Amazing, right?

112
00:06:42,591 --> 00:06:45,604
That's a girl with time on her hands.

113
00:06:45,604 --> 00:06:47,260
Better than snacking.

114
00:06:47,260 --> 00:06:51,992
Single girls lived in this place
from 1860 to 1934,

115
00:06:51,992 --> 00:06:54,025
and left a lot behind.

116
00:06:54,025 --> 00:06:55,902
Quilt included.

117
00:06:55,902 --> 00:06:58,069
Plus, this.

118
00:06:59,271 --> 00:07:02,788
- Girl's journal.
- Covers the years '28 and '29.

119
00:07:02,788 --> 00:07:05,056
Ever seen the name
Violet Polley in there?

120
00:07:05,056 --> 00:07:07,580
She's one of your main characters.

121
00:07:07,580 --> 00:07:10,580
Uh, starting on this page.

122
00:07:13,557 --> 00:07:19,155
"Ginger Swensen made it her business to turn 
Violet from a rag-a-muffin to a real Sheba."

123
00:07:19,155 --> 00:07:21,079
No kidding.
What's the date?

124
00:07:21,079 --> 00:07:25,039
December 31, 1928.
New year's eve.

125
00:07:25,039 --> 00:07:29,111
"First order of business, the hair."

126
00:07:33,755 --> 00:07:36,050
I won't even recognize myself.

127
00:07:36,050 --> 00:07:40,402
That's the idea.
Out with the old, in with the swanky.

128
00:07:40,850 --> 00:07:42,533
Where'd you say you're from, Violet?

129
00:07:42,533 --> 00:07:45,263
Oley valley, near Reading.

130
00:07:45,263 --> 00:07:47,431
I don't drink.

131
00:07:47,431 --> 00:07:50,819
I keep my mind sharp
because I'm a writer.

132
00:07:50,819 --> 00:07:53,627
Well, that's funny, 
'cause every writer I've ever met

133
00:07:53,627 --> 00:07:57,175
is fried to the hat or passed out on
Nick Bartleby's couch.

134
00:07:57,175 --> 00:07:59,286
Violet, you got a daddy?

135
00:07:59,286 --> 00:08:02,489
He's dead.
And my mother, too.

136
00:08:02,489 --> 00:08:04,949
I mean, fella.

137
00:08:04,949 --> 00:08:08,536
I did, but that's all over.

138
00:08:08,536 --> 00:08:11,640
The male persuasion are saps,
all of them.

139
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:15,429
I moved to Philadelphia because that's 
what the bus ticket I stole said on it.

140
00:08:15,429 --> 00:08:16,777
What about you?

141
00:08:16,777 --> 00:08:20,202
I heard a song on the radio
one day, back at home.

142
00:08:20,202 --> 00:08:23,052
It was the most on-the-level
song I'd ever heard,

143
00:08:23,052 --> 00:08:27,571
and when it was over,
I felt utterly different.

144
00:08:27,571 --> 00:08:28,644
What song?

145
00:08:28,644 --> 00:08:31,631
"Poor man's blues" by Bessie Smith.

146
00:08:31,631 --> 00:08:36,113
That's why I'm here,
to sell my songs to wonderful singers.

147
00:08:36,113 --> 00:08:38,453
But Bessie Smith's a negro.

148
00:08:38,453 --> 00:08:41,003
A writer needs to see the world.

149
00:08:41,003 --> 00:08:44,412
Well, it ain't the world,
it's Philadelphia.

150
00:08:44,412 --> 00:08:46,950
We'll see it tonight
at the Bartleby mansion.

151
00:08:46,950 --> 00:08:48,975
It's gonna be the berries.

152
00:08:53,734 --> 00:08:55,585
Bartleby mansion.

153
00:08:56,028 --> 00:08:57,526
You seen that place?

154
00:08:57,526 --> 00:09:00,671
I could fit 25 of my apartments in there.

155
00:09:00,671 --> 00:09:03,467
Those people were American royalty.

156
00:09:03,467 --> 00:09:05,635
Their parties were known
all over the East coast.

157
00:09:05,635 --> 00:09:07,824
Pretty good invitation for
a boarding-house girl.

158
00:09:07,824 --> 00:09:12,041
The girls who stayed here would've 
been single and on the younger side.

159
00:09:12,041 --> 00:09:14,811
Ain't a party without cute girls.

160
00:09:15,212 --> 00:09:17,005
Any Bartlebys left in Philly?

161
00:09:17,005 --> 00:09:19,959
Nick Bartleby died in a hunting
accident, I know that,

162
00:09:19,959 --> 00:09:22,340
and the only one that's 
left here is Muriel.

163
00:09:22,340 --> 00:09:26,321
And they say the old girl hasn't
left the house in years.

164
00:09:27,097 --> 00:09:28,851
Can we borrow this journal?

165
00:09:28,851 --> 00:09:34,222
Well, it's bad enough I'm letting 
you touch it with your bare hands.

166
00:09:35,060 --> 00:09:41,305
Fine. But no direct sunlight,
and no moisture.

167
00:09:52,572 --> 00:09:54,644
I was plotting my escape,

168
00:09:54,644 --> 00:09:56,838
but then I found something helpful.

169
00:10:02,441 --> 00:10:06,478
WPA transcripts.
Interviewee, Ginger Swensen.

170
00:10:06,478 --> 00:10:07,789
Name from the boarding house journal.

171
00:10:07,789 --> 00:10:09,598
Girl who cut Violet's hair.

172
00:10:09,598 --> 00:10:11,999
WPA, during the new deal,

173
00:10:11,999 --> 00:10:14,427
paid people to do interviews
with everyday Joes.

174
00:10:14,427 --> 00:10:17,922
This Ginger was one of them,
talking about her roaring 20s.

175
00:10:17,922 --> 00:10:20,574
"Before the big crash,
we whooped it up."

176
00:10:20,574 --> 00:10:24,473
According to this, biggest whoop 
of all was that new year's eve party.

177
00:10:24,473 --> 00:10:28,430
"Where a friend of mine, an inexperienced 
farm girl from Oley valley,"

178
00:10:28,430 --> 00:10:31,268
"had a bit too much to drink."

179
00:10:32,671 --> 00:10:34,767
Mine, it's my house.

180
00:10:34,767 --> 00:10:37,980
Your brother says to bed
right now, Muriel.

181
00:10:41,939 --> 00:10:46,487
You were right about liquor,
it is an artist's best friend.

182
00:10:46,487 --> 00:10:49,958
I'm full of a certain Joie de vivre.

183
00:10:50,646 --> 00:10:52,874
I'd like to sing a song for everyone.

184
00:10:52,874 --> 00:10:57,072
Betty's The Cat's Pajamas.
Hit it, Violet.

