00:14:32,859 --> 00:14:34,714
She must leave the house sometimes.

236
00:14:34,714 --> 00:14:37,304
Lie in wait while she gets
the morning paper?

237
00:14:37,304 --> 00:14:39,986
Your mom called, a few times.

238
00:14:39,986 --> 00:14:42,945
Wanted to make sure you had 
the address for the restaurant.

239
00:14:42,945 --> 00:14:46,408
She wants me to be her maid of honor.

240
00:14:46,408 --> 00:14:48,465
Buttering you up with a free meal.

241
00:14:48,465 --> 00:14:52,777
I guess, if I go,
at least she'll stop calling.

242
00:14:55,636 --> 00:15:00,782
We're investigating the murder of a girl seen
at the Bartleby new year's eve party, 1928,

243
00:15:00,782 --> 00:15:03,918
being manhandled by Felix Spyczyk.

244
00:15:03,918 --> 00:15:07,801
My grandfather did many things during 
that period that he was not proud of.

245
00:15:07,801 --> 00:15:10,154
Includes everything on his criminal record

246
00:15:10,154 --> 00:15:12,740
and whatever young girls
he was seen manhandling.

247
00:15:12,740 --> 00:15:15,576
- He told you about that?
- It was part of his job.

248
00:15:15,576 --> 00:15:18,262
- He was a procurer.
- For Bartleby.

249
00:15:18,262 --> 00:15:21,606
Whatever the great man wanted,
that's what my grandfather had to get him.

250
00:15:21,606 --> 00:15:25,609
- Booze and girls.
- Serves the guy for seven years,

251
00:15:25,609 --> 00:15:29,275
then one day, Nick Bartleby fires him.

252
00:15:29,275 --> 00:15:33,373
Plucks a clock off the mantle,
and says, "take this and hit the road."

253
00:15:33,373 --> 00:15:34,500
He made good, though.

254
00:15:34,500 --> 00:15:38,741
Sold the clock for $75 
and started Spyczyk shipping.

255
00:15:38,741 --> 00:15:42,490
Took me years,
but I tracked it down,

256
00:15:42,490 --> 00:15:43,876
bought it at auction.

257
00:15:43,876 --> 00:15:46,752
Your grandfather tell you a lot
about his days with Bartleby?

258
00:15:46,752 --> 00:15:50,390
At the end of his life,
he wanted to tell his stories.

259
00:15:50,390 --> 00:15:53,408
So I listened and made tapes of them.

260
00:15:54,103 --> 00:15:59,160
How about the night he procured 
Violet Polley at the new year's party?

261
00:15:59,160 --> 00:16:03,155
The one girl who said no to Nick Bartleby.

262
00:16:06,314 --> 00:16:09,855
She said, "my name is
Violet Polley from Oley valley,"

263
00:16:09,855 --> 00:16:13,022
"and I am a songwriter,
not a boozy floozy."

264
00:16:13,022 --> 00:16:14,955
That's her, our girl.

265
00:16:14,955 --> 00:16:19,123
Mr. Bartleby had said to me,
"get the singing dame."

266
00:16:19,123 --> 00:16:21,415
So I did.

267
00:16:24,505 --> 00:16:27,128
- Let me out!
- Aw! You call it a night.

268
00:16:27,128 --> 00:16:30,423
Okay, Spyczyk, old boy,
let her out.

269
00:16:30,423 --> 00:16:32,305
You told me bring this one.

270
00:16:32,305 --> 00:16:35,316
Not if she's violently opposed to being
in the same room with me,

271
00:16:35,316 --> 00:16:37,836
which she clearly is.

272
00:16:38,359 --> 00:16:41,236
That is, unless I'm growing on you 
and you'd like a drink. / No, thank you.

273
00:16:41,236 --> 00:16:44,292
Wait! Spyczyk, bar the door
until the lady answers one question.

274
00:16:44,292 --> 00:16:46,345
What on earth was that song?

275
00:16:46,345 --> 00:16:51,091
"One last dress" is an original 
by Violet Polley. / Oh, I know her.

276
00:16:51,091 --> 00:16:54,499
She's known to get a little soused at soirees 
and show her knickers to strangers.

277
00:16:54,499 --> 00:16:56,525
I do not!

278
00:16:57,274 --> 00:16:59,734
Well, darn it.

279
00:17:01,875 --> 00:17:05,448
Do you ever miss being part of 
the human race with the rest of us,

280
00:17:05,448 --> 00:17:09,886
or do you like life up on your mountain?

281
00:17:09,886 --> 00:17:11,663
I don't think I'm any better
than the average Joe,

282
00:17:11,663 --> 00:17:13,122
if that's what you're implying.

283
00:17:13,122 --> 00:17:15,292
I just wonder if it gets old,

284
00:17:15,292 --> 00:17:18,756
waking up each morning with
nothing to work for.

285
00:17:18,756 --> 00:17:23,178
If I had a talent like yours,
I would work, Violet Polley.

286
00:17:23,178 --> 00:17:24,573
Thank you, Mr. Bartleby.

287
00:17:24,573 --> 00:17:27,553
But as god made me,
I can only offer you charm,

288
00:17:27,553 --> 00:17:29,102
- which does nothing for you.
- True.

289
00:17:29,102 --> 00:17:30,705
And my loyal driver Spyczyk,

290
00:17:30,705 --> 00:17:33,078
half as handsome but twice
the man that I am.

291
00:17:33,078 --> 00:17:35,270
He and I can see you safely
home in my packard.

292
00:17:35,270 --> 00:17:36,884
I don't think so.

293
00:17:36,884 --> 00:17:41,799
I'm a songwriter, Mr. Bartleby,
not a boozy floozy.

294
00:17:51,136 --> 00:17:54,768
So Violet rejected Nick Bartleby.
That's a bold move.

295
00:17:54,768 --> 00:17:57,179
Here's the punch line.
Bartleby loved it.

296
00:17:57,179 --> 00:17:59,669
The one girl who says no
turns his head?

297
00:17:59,669 --> 00:18:02,551
Sent 300 flowers to her 
boarding house the next day.

298
00:18:02,551 --> 00:18:06,346
Told my grandfather to lay them
thick as oriental carpet.

299
00:18:06,346 --> 00:18:07,847
How many of those tapes you got?

300
00:18:07,847 --> 00:18:12,307
Days worth. How much would you like 
to know about Poland?

301
00:18:12,901 --> 00:18:15,133
We'll get back to you.

302
00:18:16,317 --> 00:18:20,566
"300 flowers" is the name
of an old blues standard. / Yeah?

303
00:18:20,566 --> 00:18:23,970
The lyrics go "like an oriental
carpet, thick and sweet."

304
00:18:23,970 --> 00:18:26,840
Violet was a songwriter.
Where'd you hear that?

305
00:18:26,840 --> 00:18:29,723
Singer I know covers it, Lena.

306
00:18:29,723 --> 00:18:31,702
Lena, huh?

307
00:18:33,120 --> 00:18:36,418
Let me get a look at the threads.
That's all right.

308
00:18:36,418 --> 00:18:37,478
What are you doing?

309
00:18:37,478 --> 00:18:41,131
Just making sure you look good enough to
see the woman you talk about in your sleep.

310
00:18:41,131 --> 00:18:44,703
- We're going to see her.
- Not we.

311
00:18:48,597 --> 00:18:51,228
"300 flowers" by V. Polley.

312
00:18:51,228 --> 00:18:53,279
So she got a song published.

313
00:18:53,279 --> 00:18:54,606
Few dollars in her pocket.

314
00:18:54,606 --> 00:18:56,536
Pretty upbeat song,

315
00:18:56,536 --> 00:18:58,322
but it is about a love triangle.

316
00:18:58,322 --> 00:19:00,835
Woman choosing between two men.

317
00:19:02,032 --> 00:19:06,358
"When I gave up what was ours
I met a man so kind."

318
00:19:06,358 --> 00:19:08,153
Nick Bartleby could be the kind one.

319
00:19:08,153 --> 00:19:12,891
Leaving a woman 300 flowers is kind.

320
00:19:12,891 --> 00:19:15,603
Why don't you bring it to live?

321
00:19:28,981 --> 00:19:32,518
 ¢Ü You and I ¢Ü

322
00:19:32,518 --> 00:19:35,163
 ¢Ü said good-bye ¢Ü

323
00:19:35,163 --> 00:19:39,695
 ¢Ü I thought I'd die ¢Ü

324
00:19:39,695 --> 00:19:44,363
 ¢Ü 300 flowers... ¢Ü

325
00:19:44,363 --> 00:19:50,754
 ¢Ü I've been sitting here for hours ¢Ü

326
00:19:50,754 --> 00:19:53,500
Came here to take you back,

327
00:19:53,500 --> 00:19:58,177
but it seems like you've plumb forgotten
what you and me made together.

328
00:20:00,307 --> 00:20:03,459
Hate to think of what you been 
doing to earn these flowers.

329
00:20:03,459 --> 00:20:04,933
Been working on my songs.

330
00:20:04,933 --> 00:20:08,222
Get your head on straight, Violet.
You're acting bigger than you are.

331
00:20:08,222 --> 00:20:10,933
I won't come home with you
to tend to pigs all my life.

332
00:20:10,933 --> 00:20:15,348
That's who you are, woman.
I don't want to tell you again.

333
00:20:16,237 --> 00:20:19,742
You have three guesses to guess 
which gorgeous man is downstairs

334
00:20:19,742 --> 00:20:24,585
asking for you personally.
Oh...

335
00:20:25,239 --> 00:20:27,405
I'm...

336
00:20:37,853 --> 00:20:42,015
- You been acting loose?
- Be careful, she kicks.

337
00:20:42,015 --> 00:20:45,291
I've seen it. / She's spoken for.
You scram, cake-eater.

338
00:20:45,291 --> 00:20:48,093
She speaks for herself.

339
00:20:48,093 --> 00:20:51,469
You tell people back in Oley valley
they'll be hearing about me.

340
00:20:51,469 --> 00:20:55,968
But they will never
see me back there again.

341
00:20:55,968 --> 00:20:59,100
I'll take a ride in that fancy car.

342
00:20:59,100 --> 00:21:01,531
I'd like to see the world, please.

343
00:21:01,549 --> 00:21:08,567
 ¢Ü Don't be blue, find someone new ¢Ü

344
00:21:08,567 --> 00:21:12,394
 ¢Ü 300 flowers... ¢Ü

345
00:21:13,353 --> 00:21:17,088
Sounds like your Violet chose Bartleby.

346
00:21:17,088 --> 00:21:19,994
Song says "I left behind what was ours."

347
00:21:19,994 --> 00:21:22,896
- You think that could mean a baby?
- Could be.

348
00:21:22,896 --> 00:21:27,303
Songs from this era are coded
when referring to something scandalous.

349
00:21:27,303 --> 00:21:31,467
Hometown guy thinks he's gonna get 
a second chance with the mother of his baby,

350
00:21:31,467 --> 00:21:34,944
but he gets thrown over for someone new.

351
00:21:34,944 --> 00:21:38,497
Many sad songs written about
being thrown over.

352
00:21:38,497 --> 00:21:41,580
Many lives ended over it, too.

353
00:21:46,469 --> 00:21:49,484
We got the hometown boyfriend's full name
from the boarding house journal.

354
00:21:49,484 --> 00:21:52,723
Jeb Shiner. / Anything on him 
being the father of Violet's kid?

355
00:21:52,723 --> 00:21:56,142
- Not yet, but...
- We know he didn't kill Violet.

356
00:21:56,142 --> 00:21:58,981
He was too busy with his pig.

357
00:21:59,577 --> 00:22:01,705
Farmer's almanac.

358
00:22:01,705 --> 00:22:05,656
"Jeb Shiner of reading, Pennsylvania
and his prize-winning swine,"

359
00:22:05,656 --> 00:22:08,100
"December 22, 1929."

360
00:22:08,100 --> 00:22:09,966
Three days before Violet was killed.

361
00:22:09,966 --> 00:22:12,185
And the pig contest was in California.

362
00:22:12,185 --> 00:22:15,638
In 1929, it would've taken him more than 
three days to get from there to here.

363
00:22:15,638 --> 00:22:18,815
So jeb wasn't in Philadelphia
when Violet died.

364
00:22:18,815 --> 00:22:20,988
What'd you dig up on
the Bartleby relationship?

365
00:22:20,988 --> 00:22:22,727
That the man was a dog.

366
00:22:22,727 --> 00:22:24,285
Check it out.

367
00:22:24,285 --> 00:22:27,275
Photoplay, us weekly back in the day.

368
00:22:27,275 --> 00:22:31,872
And there's Nick Bartleby looking smug
with a gal named Carmela Lefleur.

369
00:22:31,872 --> 00:22:34,383
- Who's that?
- She was Mae West-type actress.

370
00:22:34,383 --> 00:22:36,406
Had a burlesque show.
It was pretty famous,

371
00:22:36,406 --> 00:22:39,248
and she and Bartleby were 
an on-again, off-again thing.

372
00:22:39,248 --> 00:22:40,491
Where's Violet fit in?

373
00:22:40,491 --> 00:22:44,124
According to gossip?
right in the middle.

374
00:22:45,192 --> 00:22:48,394
"Nick Bartleby had the nerve
to bring his new squeeze"

375
00:22:48,394 --> 00:22:51,057
"to the black cat house in Philadelphia..."

376
00:22:51,057 --> 00:22:56,803
 ¢Ü I'm wearing secondhand hats ¢Ü

377
00:22:56,803 --> 00:22:59,516
 ¢Ü secondhand cologne ¢Ü

378
00:22:59,516 --> 00:23:05,481
 ¢Ü That's why they call me

379
00:23:05,481 --> 00:23:10,234
 ¢Ü even our piano in the parlor ¢Ü

380
00:23:10,234 --> 00:23:12,497
I don't have the right clothes
for this place.

381
00:23:12,497 --> 00:23:17,175
To look like you do in that dress,
these women would pay $200.

382
00:23:17,175 --> 00:23:20,176
Well, they only need two and a quarter.

383
00:23:22,788 --> 00:23:26,727
Nick, this might just be 
the greatest night of my entire life.

384
00:23:26,727 --> 00:23:28,631
Is it me or the dancers?

385
00:23:28,631 --> 00:23:34,677
Right now, I'm looking over your right
shoulder at Carmela Lefleur in the flesh.

386
00:23:34,677 --> 00:23:36,827
Trust me, you're not
seeing her in the flesh.

387
00:23:36,827 --> 00:23:39,727
She is absolutely sensationally beautiful

388
00:23:39,727 --> 00:23:43,033
and she'd be just the right gal
to sing my songs.

389
00:23:43,033 --> 00:23:45,571
Hello, Nick.

390
00:23:46,086 --> 00:23:48,119
Carmela.

391
00:23:48,119 --> 00:23:50,106
Oh, I see.

392
00:23:50,106 --> 00:23:52,567
So Philadelphia really is a small town.

393
00:23:52,567 --> 00:23:55,642
Violet, let's go.
We can go anywhere you'd like.

394
00:23:55,642 --> 00:23:58,667
I just don't want our evening ruined.

395
00:24:00,240 --> 00:24:02,386
Hey, pal? What's the meaning of this?

396
00:24:02,386 --> 00:24:05,814
The milk's for the girl you're baby-sitting.
Help her grow up strong.

397
00:24:05,814 --> 00:24:09,784
- Keep it to yourself, would you, Carmela?
- From now on, I will, mister.

398
00:24:11,174 --> 00:24:12,543
Don't cry, darling.

399
00:24:12,543 --> 00:24:14,255
This is nothing compared
to what I'll do to you

400
00:24:14,255 --> 00:24:18,285
if I catch your flat behind
with Nick Bartleby ever again.

401
00:24:21,983 --> 00:24:23,781
Okay.

402
00:24:23,781 --> 00:24:25,414
Carmela Lefleur put it out there.

403
00:24:25,414 --> 00:24:27,189
Don't be in public with my man.

404
00:24:27,189 --> 00:24:30,751
Could be Violet didn't take the advice 
to heart. Got spotted again.

405
00:24:30,751 --> 00:24:34,127
Got a contact for Carmela.
It's a local guy.

406
00:24:34,127 --> 00:24:37,278
- Where'd you get that?
- Name on a web site.

407
00:24:40,168 --> 00:24:43,909
"Mickey Stein. No. 1 fan."

408
00:24:44,283 --> 00:24:47,181
I know, fan sites are so cheesy.

409
00:24:47,181 --> 00:24:50,792
I put it up to attract info for my thesis.

410
00:24:50,792 --> 00:24:52,609
What's your thesis on, Mr. Stein?

411
00:24:52,609 --> 00:24:54,179
"Carmela Lefleur:

412
00:24:54,179 --> 00:24:57,340
The quintessential vaudeville girl's 
re-invention of the feminine"

413
00:24:57,340 --> 00:25:03,302
"in her work in Philadelphia
from 1927 to 1930."

414
00:25:04,435 --> 00:25:08,096
- Specific.
- And yet there's so much to tell.

415
00:25:08,096 --> 00:25:11,602
- What sparked your interest in Carmela?
- My grandfather was her dresser.

416
00:25:11,602 --> 00:25:14,121
His job was to put her clothes on her?

417
00:25:14,121 --> 00:25:18,355
Wardrobe, personal assistant, hair,
full-time confidante.

418
00:25:18,355 --> 00:25:20,902
He tell you about Carmela's
relationship with Nick Bartleby?

419
00:25:20,902 --> 00:25:25,952
Like Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, 
those two. Back and forth.

420
00:25:25,952 --> 00:25:29,145
We're looking into the murder of a girl
that went out with Bartleby.

421
00:25:29,145 --> 00:25:32,024
- Carmela wasn't happy about it.
- Murder?

422
00:25:32,024 --> 00:25:35,506
Really!
Do tell.

423
00:25:35,886 --> 00:25:38,822
We're gonna be the ones taking notes here.

424
00:25:38,822 --> 00:25:41,631
- Violet Polley. Ever hear about her?
- Sure!

425
00:25:41,631 --> 00:25:43,009
Didn't know she was murdered.

426
00:25:43,009 --> 00:25:45,014
She really pissed Carmela off,

427
00:25:45,014 --> 00:25:47,013
showing up at the burlesque show
with Bartleby.

428
00:25:47,013 --> 00:25:49,293
Well, that, that was then.

429
00:25:49,293 --> 00:25:53,037
A few months after that,
the girls made up.

430
00:25:53,037 --> 00:25:55,537
- How do you know about it?
- My granddad was there.

431
00:25:55,537 --> 00:26:01,192
It was after one of Carmela's "Dragon Lady" 
performances at The Black Cat House.

432
00:26:01,192 --> 00:26:04,154
Such gorgeous silk.

433
00:26:04,154 --> 00:26:05,918
Straight from the orient, darling.

434
00:26:05,918 --> 00:26:10,712
I've got a chinaman mad for me. 
He thinks I'd be big as tea over there.

435
00:26:11,371 --> 00:26:13,584
Hello, Carmela.

436
00:26:13,883 --> 00:26:16,212
Can I have one moment of your time?

437
00:26:16,212 --> 00:26:19,727
Autographed pictures in an hour,
behind the stage door. Shoo, fly.

438
00:26:19,727 --> 00:26:23,004
It's all right, Mickey.
Don't you know who this is?

439
00:26:23,004 --> 00:26:26,555
- It's Nick Bartleby's girl.
- Oh, dear.

440
00:26:26,555 --> 00:26:28,664
Carmela, please don't turn me away.

441
00:26:28,664 --> 00:26:31,322
I'd like to ask you something.

442
00:26:31,890 --> 00:26:34,288
Well, what is it?

443
00:26:35,089 --> 00:26:38,205
I'm a songwriter,
writing original tunes.

444
00:26:38,205 --> 00:26:42,402
I write from the soul, about the plight
of the average Jack or Jane,

445
00:26:42,402 --> 00:26:47,560
people like my parents were
humble, good people.

446
00:26:48,534 --> 00:26:51,334
Get her a soda water.

447
00:26:53,998 --> 00:26:57,171
I'm sorry. This is so strange.

448
00:26:57,171 --> 00:26:59,729
You been crying like this regular?

449
00:26:59,729 --> 00:27:02,492
Nick's in Europe.
I suppose I miss him.

450
00:27:02,492 --> 00:27:05,925
Feeling queasy, too?
Achy, like you got the flu?

451
00:27:05,925 --> 00:27:08,455
Yeah. That's it.
You had it, too?

452
00:27:08,455 --> 00:27:11,185
I did. Once.

453
00:27:11,185 --> 00:27:14,162
You're knocked up, kid.

454
00:27:14,622 --> 00:27:16,772
No.

455
00:27:17,162 --> 00:27:19,686
What would you know about it?
You don't have kids.

456
00:27:19,686 --> 00:27:22,551
It doesn't always have to end that way.

457
00:27:22,551 --> 00:27:24,909
But judging by the way you
filled out through the middle,

458
00:27:24,909 --> 00:27:27,905
it's too late for you.

459
00:27:27,905 --> 00:27:29,993
I don't know what I'll do.

460
00:27:29,993 --> 00:27:31,977
I've almost run through my savings.

461
00:27:31,977 --> 00:27:35,751
Nick's gone and I've been
too ill to get a job.

462
00:27:35,751 --> 00:27:38,976
What about your humble parents?

463
00:27:39,420 --> 00:27:42,344
They're gone.

464
00:27:42,344 --> 00:27:46,222
Um, cigarette? Uh, scotch?

465
00:27:46,222 --> 00:27:48,202
No, thank you.

466
00:27:48,202 --> 00:27:52,053
Kid, how much for a song?

467
00:27:52,053 --> 00:27:56,278
- How many do you want?
- How many you got?

468
00:27:59,627 --> 00:28:01,362
It was Nick Bartleby's baby.

469
00:28:01,362 --> 00:28:03,189
Aimee's a Bartleby.

470
00:28:03,189 --> 00:28:06,158
- That oughta blow her socks off.
